  	    "alternativeHeadline": "The NFL has problems, but not real problems (at least none that can be seen without an MRI). It\u0027s not like the NBA (where the regular season doesn\u0027t matter) or baseball (where none of the games matter) or soccer (which is mostly a media construction) or golf (where the only interesting participant is the most hated man in America) or hockey (which is played on fucking ice). The NFL\u0027s architects understand their consumer base so intimately that the product evolves faster than its critics. Still, nothing is perfect. Here are a few suggestions",
  	    "url": "http://gq.com/story/chuck-klosterman-gq-brilliant-ideas-for-football",
  	    "image": ["http://media.gq.com/photos/5583142b09f0bee564410ecf/master/pass/sports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg"],
  	    "thumbnailUrl": "http://media.gq.com/photos/5583142b09f0bee564410ecf/master/pass/sports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg",
  	    "datePublished": "2010-08-25T00:00:00.000Z",
  	    "dateModified": "2015-06-18T18:55:40.142Z",
  	    "articleSection": "News &amp; Culture",
  	    "description": "The NFL has problems, but not real problems (at least none that can be seen without an MRI). It\u0027s not like the NBA (where the regular season doesn\u0027t matter) or baseball (where none of the games matter) or soccer (which is mostly a media construction) or golf (where the only interesting participant is the most hated man in America) or hockey (which is played on fucking ice). The NFL\u0027s architects understand their consumer base so intimately that the product evolves faster than its critics. Still, nothing is perfect. Here are a few suggestions.",
  	    "articleBody": "FacebookPinterest\u000A\u000A 1. Reinvent overtime.\u000A\u000A This has been the league\u0027s most glaring on-field problem since 1974. The \u0022sudden death\u0022 format promotes conservatism, overemphasizes the kicking game, and hinges on an arbitrary coin toss. Recent off-season adjustments the league made for playoff games won\u0027t help enough. A better solution would be to boil the game down to its most fundamental element—the ability to advance the ball ten yards in four downs. NFL overtime should be like the system in college football, only more severe: Each team would get four offensive plays from the ten-yard line. No field goals, no extra points. (If you score, you have to go for two.) What could be more dramatic? \u000A\u000A 2. Tweak the enforcement of pass interference. \u000A\u000A Very often, placing the ball at the spot of an interference penalty makes sense. But nothing unjustly changes momentum like a forty-yard penalty on a pass that might not have been catchable. The league should employ two kinds of pass-interference calls: the existing rule (which would still place the ball at the spot of the foul) and an \u0022excessive downfield contact\u0022 rule (which would be five yards and an automatic first down). Referees can call \u0022excessive downfield contact\u0022 in borderline situations where the penalty is not egregious enough to justify a massive change in field position. The only exception would be any interference in the end zone; that should always move the ball to the one-yard line automatically (in order to keep Hail Marys relevant).\u000A\u000A 3. Microscopically increase the success of onside kicks.\u000A\u000A Onside kicks work about 24 percent of the time. But that\u0027s a misleading figure; they rarely work if the opponent knows they\u0027re coming. From an entertainment perspective, it would be nice to increase the likelihood of the kicking team recovering its onside attempt, but not by too much—if teams suddenly recovered 40 percent, the game would become a farce. So how do we slightly increase that possibility? By changing where the receiving team lines up. Right now, it\u0027s ten yards from where the ball is kicked. Make that fifteen yards, which would force the receiving team to charge forward once the ball is kicked. It wouldn\u0027t change the metrics dramatically, but it would give the trailing team slightly better odds.\u000A\u000A 4. Use throwback uniforms at least half the time. \u000A\u000A Who doesn\u0027t find this charming?\u000A\u000A 5. Instead of talking about Brett Favre\u0027s future, talk about the future of the NFL\u0027s collective-bargaining agreement. \u000A\u000A Unless there\u0027s an extension, the league\u0027s CBA with players expires next March. This is a complex legal problem, but it boils down to this: The end of the CBA means the end of the salary cap, and that would almost certainly lead to a lockout. The evaporation of the cap could also destroy the competitive balance that keeps pro football from growing stale. (A cash-rich franchise like the Cowboys could become the Yankees.) Nothing will impact the future of the NFL more than the outcome of this dispute.\u000A\u000AChuck Klosterman is the author of Eating the Dinosaur. Follow him on Twitter @CKlosterman.",
  	    "author": ["Chuck Klosterman","Headcase Design"],
  	    "keywords": ["Sports","Lists","NFL Preview 2010","Chuck Klosterman","Football","NFL"]
