huck%20Klosterman%20on%20Five%20Brilliant%20Ideas%20to%20Make%20Football%20Better&amp;via=GQMagazine&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fchuck-klosterman-gq-brilliant-ideas-for-football" target="_blank" aria-label="Twitter" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-twitter.0"><span class="icon" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-twitter.0.0"></span><span class="label" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.1.3.0.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-twitter.0.1">Twitter</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><h2 class="dek" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.3">The NFL has problems, but not real problems (at least none that can be seen without an MRI). It&#39;s not like the NBA (where the regular season doesn&#39;t matter) or baseball (where none of the games matter) or soccer (which is mostly a media construction) or golf (where the only interesting participant is the most hated man in America) or hockey (which is played on fucking ice). The NFL&#39;s architects understand their consumer base so intimately that the product evolves faster than its critics. Still, nothing is perfect. Here are a few suggestions</h2><div class="body-text" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4"><div class="embed image" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.0"><figure class="embedded-image" data-type="image"><div class="image-content"><div class="component-rendition"><div class="component-image loaded"><span><img src="http://media.gq.com/photos/5583142b09f0bee564410ecd/master/w_806/sports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg" alt="sports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg"></span></div></div><div class="component-social-share default"><div class="share-item facebook" data-href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fchuck-klosterman-gq-brilliant-ideas-for-football&amp;t=sports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fchuck-klosterman-gq-brilliant-ideas-for-football&amp;t=sports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg" target="_blank" aria-label="Facebook"><span class="icon"></span><span class="label">Facebook</span></a></div><div class="share-item pinterest" data-href="https://www.pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fchuck-klosterman-gq-brilliant-ideas-for-football&amp;media=http%3A%2F%2Fmedia.gq.com%2Fphotos%2F5583142b09f0bee564410ecd%2F1%3A1%2Fw_680%2Cc_limit%2Fsports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg&amp;description=sports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg"><a href="https://www.pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fchuck-klosterman-gq-brilliant-ideas-for-football&amp;media=http%3A%2F%2Fmedia.gq.com%2Fphotos%2F5583142b09f0bee564410ecd%2F1%3A1%2Fw_680%2Cc_limit%2Fsports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg&amp;description=sports-2010-09-football-package-five-brilliant-ideas-five-brilliant-ideas_628x434.jpg" target="_blank" aria-label="Pinterest"><span class="icon"></span><span class="label">Pinterest</span></a></div></div></div></figure></div><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.1"> <strong>1. Reinvent overtime.</strong></p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.2"> This has been the league&#x2019;s most glaring on-field problem since 1974. The &quot;sudden death&quot; format promotes conservatism, overemphasizes the kicking game, and hinges on an arbitrary coin toss. Recent off-season adjustments the league made for playoff games won&#x2019;t help enough. A better solution would be to boil the game down to its most fundamental element&#x2014;the ability to advance the ball ten yards in four downs. NFL overtime should be like the system in college football, only more severe: Each team would get four offensive plays from the ten-yard line. No field goals, no extra points. (If you score, you have to go for two.) What could be more dramatic? </p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.3"> <strong>2. Tweak the enforcement of pass interference. </strong></p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.5"> Very often, placing the ball at the spot of an interference penalty makes sense. But nothing unjustly changes momentum like a forty-yard penalty on a pass that might not have been catchable. The league should employ two kinds of pass-interference calls: the existing rule (which would still place the ball at the spot of the foul) and an &quot;excessive downfield contact&quot; rule (which would be five yards and an automatic first down). Referees can call &quot;excessive downfield contact&quot; in borderline situations where the penalty is not egregious enough to justify a massive change in field position. The only exception would be any interference in the end zone; that should always move the ball to the one-yard line automatically (in order to keep Hail Marys relevant).</p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.6"> <strong>3. Microscopically increase the success of onside kicks.</strong></p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.7"> Onside kicks work about 24 percent of the time. But that&#x2019;s a misleading figure; they rarely work if the opponent knows they&#x2019;re coming. From an entertainment perspective, it would be nice to increase the likelihood of the kicking team recovering its onside attempt, but not by too much&#x2014;if teams suddenly recovered 40 percent, the game would become a farce. So how do we slightly increase that possibility? By changing where the receiving team lines up. Right now, it&#x2019;s ten yards from where the ball is kicked. Make that fifteen yards, which would force the receiving team to charge forward once the ball is kicked. It wouldn&#x2019;t change the metrics dramatically, but it would give the trailing team slightly better odds.</p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.8"> <strong>4. Use throwback uniforms at least half the time. </strong></p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.9"> Who doesn&#x2019;t find this charming?</p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.a"> <strong>5. Instead of talking about Brett Favre&#x2019;s future, talk about the future of the NFL&#x2019;s collective-bargaining agreement. </strong></p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.b"> Unless there&#x2019;s an extension, the league&#x2019;s CBA with players expires next March. This is a complex legal problem, but it boils down to this: The end of the CBA means the end of the salary cap, and that would almost certainly lead to a lockout. The evaporation of the cap could also destroy the competitive balance that keeps pro football from growing stale. (A cash-rich franchise like the Cowboys could become the Yankees.) Nothing will impact the future of the NFL more than the outcome of this dispute.</p><p data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.4.c"><em>Chuck Klosterman is the author of </em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Eating-Dinosaur-Chuck-Klosterman/dp/1416544208">Eating the Dinosaur</a><em>. Follow him on Twitter <a href="http://twitter.com/cklosterman">@CKlosterman</a>.</em></p></div><div class="grid" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5"><div class="row" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0"><div class="col col-sm-15" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0"><div class="component-topics" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0"><ul data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0"><li data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-0"><a href="../search?tags=Sports" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-0.0">Sports</a></li><li data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-1"><a href="../search?tags=Lists" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-1.0">Lists</a></li><li data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-2"><a href="../search?tags=NFL%2520Preview%25202010" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-2.0">NFL Preview 2010</a></li><li data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-3"><a href="../search?tags=Chuck%2520Klosterman" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-3.0">Chuck Klosterman</a></li><li data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-4"><a href="../search?tags=Football" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-4.0">Football</a></li><li data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-5"><a href="../search?tags=NFL" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.0.0.0.$topic-item-5.0">NFL</a></li></ul></div></div><div class="col col-sm-5" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.1"><div class="social-share-bottom" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0"><div class="component-social-share default" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0"><div class="share-item facebook" data-href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fchuck-klosterman-gq-brilliant-ideas-for-football&amp;t=Chuck%20Klosterman%20on%20Five%20Brilliant%20Ideas%20to%20Make%20Football%20Better" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gq.com%2Fstory%2Fchuck-klosterman-gq-brilliant-ideas-for-football&amp;t=Chuck%20Klosterman%20on%20Five%20Brilliant%20Ideas%20to%20Make%20Football%20Better" target="_blank" aria-label="Facebook" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0"><span class="icon" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0.0"></span><span class="label" data-reactid=".13hreryyosg.1.1.0.0.5.0.1.0.0.0:$share-item-facebook.0.1">Facebook</span></a></div><div class="share-item twitter" data-href="https://twitter.com/share?text=Chuck%20Klosterman%20on%20Five%20Brilliant%20Ide